definition.value: A serine/threonine kinase inhibitor that specifically inhibits human mutant serine/threonine kinase (B-Raf)

Colourless, endogenous or exogenous pigment precursors that may be transformed by biological mechanisms into coloured compounds. They are used in biochemical assays and in diagnosis as indicators, particularly in the form of enzyme substrates.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of squalene synthase (EC 2.5.1.21).
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of lysine 2,3-aminomutase.
An antagonist at the insulin-like growth factor receptor 1.
Any compound that inhibits one or more steps in the pathway leading to the synthesis of ergosterol.
Any substance that can induce the release of histamine from mast cells.
A generally pharmacologically inactive substance that is formulated with the active ingredient of a medication.
Any substance that accelerates defecation. Compare with laxatives, which are substances that ease defecation (usually by softening faeces). A substance can be both a laxative and a cathartic.
A chemical additive used to toughen or harden a polymer material by cross-linking of polymer chains.
An inhibitor of peroxidases (EC 1.11.1.*) that inhibits the action of catalase (EC 1.11.1.6).
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits any of the peroxidases (EC 1.11.1.*).
An agonist that binds to and activates platelet-activating factor receptors.
Any compound that inhibits the action of an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
An aminoacyl tRNA synthetase inhibitor that specifically inhibits the action of seryl-tRNA synthetase.
Any compound that inhibits the action of alanine racemase (EC 5.1.1.1).
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of an isomerase (EC 5.*.*.*).
An acid--amino-acid ligase inhibitor that inhibits the action of a D-alanine--D-alanine ligase (EC 6.3.2.4).
An acid--amino-acid ligase inhibitor that inhibits the action of a glutamate--cysteine ligase (EC 6.3.2.2)
Any inhibitor of a C-N bond-forming ligase (EC 6.3.*.*).

Any enzyme inhibitor that inhibits a ligase (EC 6.*.*.*). Ligases are enzymes that catalyse the joining of two molecules with concomitant hydrolysis of the diphosphate bond in ATP or a similar triphosphate.
Any inhibitor of a C-C bond-forming ligase (EC 6.4.*.*).
A ligase inhibitor which inhibits the action of a phosphoric ester bond-forming ligase (EC 6.5.*.*).
Any prokaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in a bacterium.
Any bacterial metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Escherichia coli.
Any  metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in eukaryotes, the taxon that include members of the fungi, plantae and animalia kingdoms.
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in fungi, the kingdom that includes microorganisms such as the yeasts and moulds.
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in plants, the kingdom that include flowering plants, conifers and other gymnosperms.
Any eukaryotic metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in animals that include diverse creatures from sponges, insects to humans.
Any animal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in mammals.

Any of the group of eight water-soluble vitamins originally thought to be a single compound (vitamin B) that play important roles in cell metabolism. The group comprises vitamin B1, B2, B3, B5, B6, B7, B9, and B12. (Around 20 other compounds were once thought to be B vitamins but are no longer classified as such.)
Any mammalian metabolite  produced during a metabolic reaction in humans (Homo sapiens).
Any mammalian metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in mouse (Mus musculus).
Any  fungal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae).
Any metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in prokaryotes, the taxon that include members of the bacteria kingdom.
Any bacterial metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Streptococcus pneumoniae.
Any fungal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in the mold,  Aspergillus.
Any fungal metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in the mold, Chaetomium.
An enzyme inhibitor that interferes with the action of S-phase kinase-associated protein 2 (Skp2).
Any protein kinase inhibitor that interferes with the action of mitogen-activated protein kinase.
An effector that binds to and activates soluble guanylate cyclase (EC 4.6.1.2).
